ook Young-ran/Grace\n| <ref name=eden>{{cite web|url=http://news.donga.com/3/all/20080605/8586827/1|title=\uc774\uc5f0\ud76c, MBC \u2018\uc5d0\ub374\uc758 \ub3d9\ucabd\u2019\uc11c \uc1a1\uc2b9\ud5cc\uacfc \ud638\ud761|date=5 June 2008|website=The Donga Ilbo|language=ko}}</ref> \n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Paradise Ranch]]'' \n| Lee Da-ji\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]\n| <ref name=ranch>{{cite web|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2011022207133654006|title='\ud30c\ub77c\ub2e4\uc774\uc2a4 \ubaa9\uc7a5' \uc774\uc5f0\ud76c \"\uc81c \uc5f0\uae30\uac00 \uc88b\uc544\uc84c\ub2e4\uace0\uc694?\"(\uc778\ud130\ubdf0)|date=22 February 2011|website=10Asia|language=ko}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Phantom (TV series)|Phantom]]'' \n| Yoo Kang-mi\n| <ref name=phantom>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/10316|title=Lee Yeon-hee to play female detective in upcoming SBS TV series|date=21 March 2012|website=10Asia}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2013\n| ''[[Gu Family Book]]'' \n| Yoon Seo-hwa (Special appearance) \n| rowspan=\"3\" | MBC\n| <ref name=gu>{{cite web|last=Park|first=Hani|title=Lee Yeon Hee to Make Special Appearance in the Upcoming Drama|url=http://mwave.interest.me/news/newsdetail/print/popup.m?searchNewsVO.news_id=201302041309_28211|work=enewsWorld|publisher=CJ E&M|accessdate=4 February 2013|date=4 February 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Miss Korea (TV series)|Miss Korea]]''\n| Oh Ji-young\n| <ref name=korea>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/74979|title=Lee Yeon-hee, Lee Sun-kyun to Pair Up for New MBC Series|date=31 October 2013|website=10Asia}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Splendid Politics]]''\n| Princess Jeongmyeong\n| <ref name=splendid>{{cite web|url=http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2015/04/398_176687.html|title=Gwanghaegun returns in 'factional' drama|date=7 April 2015|work=The Korea Times}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2017\n| ''[[Reunited Worlds]]''\n|  Jung Jung-won\n| SBS\n| <ref name=reunited>{{cite web|url=http://www.hancinema.net/lee-yeon-hee-to-star-in-sbs-reunited-worlds-106535.html|title=Lee Yeon-hee to star in SBS \"Reunited Worlds\"|work=Hancinema|publisher=Ilgan Sports|date=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[The Package (TV series)|''The Package'']]\n| Yoon So-so\n| [[jTBC]]\n| <ref name=package>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3022149|title=Jung Yong-hwa and Lee Yeon-hee sign on for JTBC\u2019s \u2018The Package\u2019|work=Korea JoongAng Daily|date=4 August 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2020\n| ''[[The Game: Towards Zero]]''\n| Seo Jun Young\n| rowspan=2|MBC\n| <ref>{{cite web|last1=Kim|first1=Myung-mi|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=609&aid=0000149051|date=August 2, 2019|work=Newsen|publisher=Naver|title=\uc774\uc5f0\ud76c \uce21 \u201cMBC \u2018\ub354\uac8c\uc784\u2019 \ucd9c\uc5f0\ud655\uc815\u201d \uc625\ud0dd\uc5f0\uacfc \ud638\ud761(\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5)|language=ko|accessdate=September 15, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[SF8]]: Female Shaman'' \n| \n| \n|}\n\n==Variety show==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:700px\"\n|-\n! width=10|Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Network\n! Ref. \n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Island Trio|Island Trio 2]]'' \n| Cast member\n| [[O'live]], [[tvN]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3047753&cloc=joongangdaily|title=Olive\u2019s \u2018Island Trio\u2019 announces its new cast|date=5 May 2018|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Music video appearances==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:700px\"\n|-\n! width=10|Year\n! Song title\n! Artist\n! Ref. \n|-\n| rowspan=3|2001\n| \"Alone\" \n| [[Moon Hee-joon]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.donga.com/List/http/3/all/20110325/35880862/4|title= \uc774\uc5f0\ud76c, \uc911\ud559\uc0dd \uc2dc\uc808 \ubaa8\uc2b5 \u2018\uc6d0\ud310 \ubd88\ubcc0\uc758 \ubc95\uce59\u2019 \uc785\uc99d \u2018\ub180\ub77c\uc6cc!\u2019|date=25 March 2011|website=The Donga Ilbo|language=ko}}</ref> \n|-\n| \"Our Story\"\n| [[Moon Hee-joon]] feat. [[Shinvi|Oh Sang-eun]]\n| \n|-\n| \"Thanks God\"\n| [[Kangta]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=5|2002\n| \"Condition of My Heart\"\n| [[Fly to the Sky]]\n| \n|-\n| \"Hero\"\n| [[Shinhwa]]\n| \n|-\n| \"Memories\"\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Kangta]]\n| \n|-\n| \"Pine Tree\"\n| \n|-\n| \"Propose\"\n| \n|-\n| 2003\n| \"Habit\"\n| [[Fly to the Sky]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2|2004\n| \"My Little Princess\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[TVXQ]]\n|\n|-\n| \"The Way U Are\"\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2005\n| \"Persona\"\n| [[Kangta]]\n| \n|-\n| \"One\"\n| [[TVXQ]]\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| \"[[Timeless (Zhang Liyin song)|Timeless]]\"\n| [[Zhang Liyin]] feat. [[Junsu|Xia]] \n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=111&aid=0000042633|title=\uc7a5\ub9ac\uc778 \ubba4\ube44, \ud55c\uacbd-\uc774\uc5f0\ud76c-\uc2dc\uc6d0 \ucd9c\uc5f0|date=31 August 2008|website=inews24|language=ko}}</ref> \n|-\n| rowspan=3|2008\n| \"Star Wish (I Will)\"\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Zhang Liyin]]\n|\n|-\n| \"The Left Shore of Happiness\"\n| \n|-\n| \"M-net Love Song 2008\"\n| \n|-\n| 2009\n| \"Wizard Of Oz\"\n| [[Clazziquai]]\n| \n|-\n| 2010\n| \"Miss You\"\n| [[S.M. The Ballad]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2010113008382066712|title=S.M. The Ballad unveils music video for title track|date=30 November 2010|website=10Asia}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:South Korean filmographies]]\n", "name_user": "Seokgjin", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision series", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Yeon-hee_filmography"}
{"title_page": "National Garden, Athens", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=February 2009}}\n{{Infobox park\n| name = \u0395\u03b8\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u039a\u03ae\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2<br /> National Gardens\n| alt_name = \u0392\u03b1\u03c3\u03b9\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u039a\u03ae\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2<br /> Royal Gardens\n| photo = National Gardens.jpg\n| photo_width = 300\n| photo_caption = Interior view\n| type = Public park\n| location = [[Athens]], [[Greece]]\n| coords = {{coord|37|58|27|N|23|44|18|E|region:GR|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| area = {{convert|15.5|ha}}\n| created = 1838\n| operator = \n| visitation_num = \n| status = Open year round\n| map = Greece Athens central\n| map_width = 272px\n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = Location within central Athens\n|publictransit = {{OASA icons|M|15}} {{OASA icons|M2}}{{OASA icons|M3}} [[Syntagma metro station|Syntagma station]]\n}}\n\n[[File:National park of Athens1.JPG|thumb|220px|The National Garden in central Athens, commissioned by [[Amalia of Oldenburg|Amalia]], the first Queen of modern Greece.]]\n\nThe '''National Garden'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.athensinfoguide.com/wtsgarden.htm |title=The National Garden |publisher=Athens Info Guide , 2004-2009 |accessdate=2010-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.athensguide.com/gardens.html |title=The National Garden, Zappion, Panathenaic Stadium and the Temple of Olympian Zeus |publisher=Athens Survival Guide |accessdate=2010-03-09}}</ref> (formerly the '''Royal Garden''') ({{lang-el|\u0395\u03b8\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u039a\u03ae\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2}}) is a public park of {{convert|15.5|ha}} in the center of the [[Greece|Greek]] capital, [[Athens]]. It is located between the districts of [[Kolonaki]] and [[Pangrati]], directly behind the [[Hellenic Parliament|Greek Parliament building]] (The Old Palace) and continues to the South to the area where the [[Zappeion]] is located, across from the [[Panathinaiko Stadium|Panathenaiko]] or Kalimarmaro [[Olympic Stadium]] of the [[1896 Olympic Games]]. The Garden also encloses some ancient ruins, tambourines and [[Corinthian Order|Corinthian]] capitals of columns, [[mosaic]]s, and other features. On the Southeast side are the busts of [[Ioannis Kapodistrias]], the first [[governor]] of Greece, and of the [[Philhellenism|Philhellene]] [[Jean-Gabriel Eynard]]. On the South side are the busts of the celebrated Greek poets [[Dionysios Solomos]], author of the Greek National Hymn, and [[Aristotelis Valaoritis]].\n\n==History==\nThe Royal Garden was commissioned by [[Amalia of Oldenburg|Queen Amalia]] in 1838 and completed by 1840. It was designed by the German agronomist Friedrich Schmidt who imported over 500 species of plants and a variety of animals including peacocks, ducks, and turtles. Unfortunately for many of the plants, the dry Mediterranean climate proved too harsh and they did not survive. Other botanists planning and managing the garden include [[Karl Nikolas Fraas]], [[Theodor von Heldreich]] and [[Spyridon Miliarakis]].\n\nA part of the upper garden, behind the Old Palace, was fenced off and was the    private refuge of the King and Queen. The garden was open to the public in the afternoons.\n\nClose to the garden in 1878 the neo-classical [[Zappeion]] Hall was built. It was donated by [[Evangelis Zappas]] and designed by [[Theophil Freiherr von Hansen]]. Zappas had started the Zappian Olympic Games, a precursor to the modern [[Olympic Games]]. The Zappeion was the Olympic village for the 1896 [[Summer Olympics]] in Athens and also as a venue for the fencing events. Starting in the 1920s, the area in front of the Zappeion was also a major transportation hub for [[Athens Tram|trams]] and buses. Today it is used for public exhibitions. \n\n===The Royal Garden===\nThe Royal Garden was the scene of an unusual turning point in Greek history. In 1920, at the end of [[World War I]], Greece under [[Alexander of Greece|King Alexander]] and the government of [[Eleftherios Venizelos]] remained committed to the [[Megali Idea]] ([[Greek language|Greek]] for The Great Idea) that Greece should gain control of portions of [[Asia Minor]]. In 1919, they began the [[Greco-Turkish War (1919-1922)|Greco-Turkish War]] with the support of their former allies [[United Kingdom|Britain]] and [[France]]. While walking in the Garden on September 30, 1920, King Alexander was bitten by a pet monkey (whose pet it is not revealed) and he died of [[sepsis]] three weeks later. His death ushered the return of his deposed father, [[Constantine I of Greece|King Constantine I]] who had been deposed for his pro-[[Germany|German]] sympathies during the First World War. Upon his return to power, King Constantine assisted in the defeat of his political nemesis, Venizelos in the November 1920 General Election. The new Prime Minister, [[Dimitrios Gounaris]], a monarchist, began replacing the Venezelist military staff with officers more loyal to the new King. As a result of this change in political environment and it is argued, the reduction in military experience by the Army's General Staff, the Allied Powers withdrew their support. The result was the 1922 [[Great Fire of Smyrna]], the defeat of Greek troops in Turkey with exodus of Greek refugees and the 1923 [[Exchange of populations between Greece and Turkey]] known collectively by the Greeks as the Asia Minor \"Catastrophe. [[Winston Churchill]] wrote, \"it is perhaps no exaggeration to remark that a quarter of a million persons died of this      monkey's bite.\"<ref>Churchill, p. 409, quoted (for example) in Pentzopoulos, p. 39.</ref>\n\n===The National Garden===\n[[File:A sundial at the National Gardens of Athens.JPG|thumb|200px|A child and woman looking at a [[sundial]] installed at the National Gardens of Athens in 2013]]\n\nIn the 1920s the park was opened to the public and renamed \"National Garden\". In honour of Amalia of Greece, the entrance was moved to the 12 palms she planted and the street in front was renamed Queen Amalia Avenue. Since then the National Garden, is open to the public from sunrise to sunset. \n\n[[Henry Miller]] wrote in 1939:\n<blockquote>\n\"It remains in my memory like no other park I have known. It is the quintessence of a park, the thing one feels sometimes in looking at a canvas or dreaming of a place one would like to be in and never finds.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.greece-athens.com/place.php?place_id=109 |title=National Gardens |publisher= Travel to Athens, Greece |accessdate=2010-03-09}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn 2004 the Greek state gave the garden for 90 years to the city of Athens.\n\n==Services==\nThe National Garden, is open to the public from sunrise to sunset. The main entrance is on Leoforos Amalias, the street named after the Queen who envisioned this park. You can also enter the garden from one of three other gates: the central one, on Vasilissis Sophias Avenue, another on [[Herodou Attikou Street]] and the third gate connects the National Garden with the Zappeion park area. In the National Garden there are a duck pond, a Botanical Museum, a small cafe and a Children's Library and playground.\n\n==Gallery==\n<center>\n<gallery>\nFile:Royal Gardens 1905.png|The Royal Garden c.1905\nFile:20100411 athina100.JPG|View of the entrance\nFile:\"\u0397 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u0392\u03cd\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd\u03b1\", \u03bb\u03b5\u03c9\u03c6\u03cc\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u0392\u03b1\u03c3\u03b9\u03bb\u03af\u03c3\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2 \u038c\u03bb\u03b3\u03b1\u03c2 - panoramio (1).jpg|Monument to [[Lord Byron]]\nFile:Athens - National Gardens - monument 02.jpg|Statue of [[Ioannis Varvakis]]\nFile:National park of Athens5.JPG|Antiquities within the National Garden\nFile:Palm trees in the Athens' National Garden - panoramio.jpg|Palm trees\nFile:Attica 06-13 Athens 13 National Garden.jpg|Ponds in National Garden\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Greece}}\n*[[Greek gardens]]\n*[[:Category:Landscape design history|Landscape design history]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.greece-athens.com/place.php?place_id=109 Athens City Guide.]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|National Garden of Athens}}\n\n{{Landmarks in Athens}}\n\n[[Category:1840 establishments in Greece]]\n[[Category:Areas of Athens]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Athens]]\n[[Category:Parks in Greece]]\n[[Category:Gardens in Greece]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Athens]]\n[[Category:Geography of Athens]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=February 2009}}\n{{Infobox park\n| name = \u0395\u03b8\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u039a\u03ae\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2<br /> National Gardens\n| alt_name = \u0392\u03b1\u03c3\u03b9\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u039a\u03ae\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2<br /> Royal Gardens\n| photo = National Gardens.jpg\n| photo_width = 300\n| photo_caption = Interior view\n| type = Public park\n| location = [[Athens]], [[Greece]]\n| coords = {{coord|37|58|27|N|23|44|18|E|region:GR|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| area = {{convert|15.5|ha}}\n| created = 1838\n| operator = \n| visitation_num = \n| status = Open year round\n| map = Greece Athens central\n| map_width = 272px\n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = Location within central Athens\n|publictransit = {{OASA icons|M|15}} {{OASA icons|M2}}{{OASA icons|M3}} [[Syntagma metro station|Syntagma station]]\n}}\n\n[[File:National park of Athens1.JPG|thumb|220px|The National Garden in central Athens, commissioned by [[Amalia of Oldenburg|Amalia]], the first Queen of modern Greece.]]\n\nThe '''National Garden'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.athensinfoguide.com/wtsgarden.htm |title=The National Garden |publisher=Athens Info Guide , 2004-2009 |accessdate=2010-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.athensguide.com/gardens.html |title=The National Garden, Zappion, Panathenaic Stadium and the Temple of Olympian Zeus |publisher=Athens Survival Guide |accessdate=2010-03-09}}</ref> (formerly the '''Royal Garden''') ({{lang-el|\u0395\u03b8\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u039a\u03ae\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2}}) is a public park of {{convert|15.5|ha}} in the center of the [[Greece|Greek]] capital, [[Athens]]. It is located between the districts of [[Kolonaki]] and [[Pangrati]], directly behind the [[Hellenic Parliament|Greek Parliament building]] (The Old Palace) and continues to the South to the area where the [[Zappeion]] is located, across from the [[Panathinaiko Stadium|Panathenaiko]] or Kalimarmaro [[Olympic Stadium]] of the [[1896 Olympic Games]]. The Garden also encloses some ancient ruins, tambourines and [[Corinthian Order|Corinthian]] capitals of columns, [[mosaic]]s, and other features. On the Southeast side are the busts of [[Ioannis Kapodistrias]], the first [[governor]] of Greece, and of the [[Philhellenism|Philhellene]] [[Jean-Gabriel Eynard]]. On the South side are the busts of the celebrated Greek poets [[Dionysios Solomos]], author of the Greek National Hymn, and [[Aristotelis Valaoritis]].\n\n==History==\nThe Royal Garden was commissioned by [[Amalia of Oldenburg|Queen Amalia]] in 1838 and completed by 1840. It was designed by the German agronomist Friedrich Schmidt who imported over 500 species of plants and a variety of animals including peacocks, ducks, and turtles. Unfortunately for many of the plants, the dry Mediterranean climate proved too harsh and they did not survive. Other botanists planning and managing the garden include [[Karl Nikolas Fraas]], [[Theodor von Heldreich]] and [[Spyridon Miliarakis]].\n\nA part of the upper garden, behind the Old Palace, was fenced off and was the private refuge of the King and Queen. The garden was open to the public in the afternoons.\n\nClose to the garden in 1878 the neo-classical [[Zappeion]] Hall was built. It was donated by [[Evangelis Zappas]] and designed by [[Theophil Freiherr von Hansen]]. Zappas had started the Zappian Olympic Games, a precursor to the modern [[Olympic Games]]. The Zappeion was the Olympic village for the 1896 [[Summer Olympics]] in Athens and also as a venue for the fencing events. Starting in the 1920s, the area in front of the Zappeion was also a major transportation hub for [[Athens Tram|trams]] and buses. Today it is used for public exhibitions. \n\n===The Royal Garden===\nThe Royal Garden was the scene of an unusual turning point in Greek history. In 1920, at the end of [[World War I]], Greece under [[Alexander of Greece|King Alexander]] and the government of [[Eleftherios Venizelos]] remained committed to the [[Megali Idea]] ([[Greek language|Greek]] for The Great Idea) that Greece should gain control of portions of [[Asia Minor]]. In 1919, they began the [[Greco-Turkish War (1919-1922)|Greco-Turkish War]] with the support of their former allies [[United Kingdom|Britain]] and [[France]]. While walking in the Garden on September 30, 1920, King Alexander was bitten by a pet monkey (whose pet it is not revealed) and he died of [[sepsis]] three weeks later. His death ushered the return of his deposed father, [[Constantine I of Greece|King Constantine I]] who had been deposed for his pro-[[Germany|German]] sympathies during the First World War. Upon his return to power, King Constantine assisted in the defeat of his political nemesis, Venizelos in the November 1920 General Election. The new Prime Minister, [[Dimitrios Gounaris]], a monarchist, began replacing the Venezelist military staff with officers more loyal to the new King. As a result of this change in political environment and it is argued, the reduction in military experience by the Army's General Staff, the Allied Powers withdrew their support. The result was the 1922 [[Great Fire of Smyrna]], the defeat of Greek troops in Turkey with exodus of Greek refugees and the 1923 [[Exchange of populations between Greece and Turkey]] known collectively by the Greeks as the Asia Minor \"Catastrophe. [[Winston Churchill]] wrote, \"it is perhaps no exaggeration to remark that a quarter of a million persons died of this monkey's bite.\"<ref>Churchill, p. 409, quoted (for example) in Pentzopoulos, p. 39.</ref>\n\n===The National Garden===\n[[File:A sundial at the National Gardens of Athens.JPG|thumb|200px|A child and woman looking at a [[sundial]] installed at the National Gardens of Athens in 2013]]\n\nIn the 1920s the park was opened to the public and renamed \"National Garden\". In honour of Amalia of Greece, the entrance was moved to the 12 palms she planted and the street in front was renamed Queen Amalia Avenue. Since then the National Garden, is open to the public from sunrise to sunset. \n\n[[Henry Miller]] wrote in 1939:\n<blockquote>\n\"It remains in my memory like no other park I have known. It is the quintessence of a park, the thing one feels sometimes in looking at a canvas or dreaming of a place one would like to be in and never finds.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.greece-athens.com/place.php?place_id=109 |title=National Gardens |publisher= Travel to Athens, Greece |accessdate=2010-03-09}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn 2004 the Greek state gave the garden for 90 years to the city of Athens.\n\n==Services==\nThe National Garden, is open to the public from sunrise to sunset. The main entrance is on Leoforos Amalias, the street named after the Queen who envisioned this park. You can also enter the garden from one of three other gates: the central one, on Vasilissis Sophias Avenue, another on [[Herodou Attikou Street]] and the third gate connects the National Garden with the Zappeion park area. In the National Garden there are a duck pond, a Botanical Museum, a small cafe and a Children's Library and playground.\n\n==Gallery==\n<center>\n<gallery>\nFile:Royal Gardens 1905.png|The Royal Garden c.1905\nFile:20100411 athina100.JPG|View of the entrance\nFile:\"\u0397 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u0392\u03cd\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd\u03b1\", \u03bb\u03b5\u03c9\u03c6\u03cc\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u0392\u03b1\u03c3\u03b9\u03bb\u03af\u03c3\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2 \u038c\u03bb\u03b3\u03b1\u03c2 - panoramio (1).jpg|Monument to [[Lord Byron]]\nFile:Athens - National Gardens - monument 02.jpg|Statue of [[Ioannis Varvakis]]\nFile:National park of Athens5.JPG|Antiquities within the National Garden\nFile:Palm trees in the Athens' National Garden - panoramio.jpg|Palm trees\nFile:Attica 06-13 Athens 13 National Garden.jpg|Ponds in National Garden\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Greece}}\n*[[Greek gardens]]\n*[[:Category:Landscape design history|Landscape design history]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.greece-athens.com/place.php?place_id=109 Athens City Guide.]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|National Garden of Athens}}\n\n{{Landmarks in Athens}}\n\n[[Category:1840 establishments in Greece]]\n[[Category:Areas of Athens]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Athens]]\n[[Category:Parks in Greece]]\n[[Category:Gardens in Greece]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Athens]]\n[[Category:Geography of Athens]]\n", "name_user": "109.151.193.82", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eThe Royal Garden)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Garden,_Athens"}
{"title_page": "Fay Honey Knopp", "text_new": "'''Fay \"Honey\" Knopp''' ({{nee}} '''Irving''', August 15, 1918 \u2013 August 10, 1995) was a [[Quakers|Quaker]] minister, peace and civil rights advocate, and [[Prison abolition movement|prison abolitionist]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nFay Birdie Irving was born on  August 15, 1918 in [[Bridgeport, Connecticut|Bridgeport]], [[Connecticut]] to Mollie Feldman and Alexander Ajolo Irving, a Russian-Jewish emigree. She graduated from [[Warren Harding High School]] as valedictorian in 1935. After high school, she became a women's fashion buyer and in 1941 married Burton Knopp. Together they had two children, Sari and Connecticut politician [[Alex Knopp]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WSaMu4F06AQC&pg=PA347|title=Notable American Women: A Biographical Dictionary Completing the Twentieth Century|last=Ware|first=Susan|date=2004|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=9780674014886|language=en}}</ref> She studied at the [[University of Hartford|Hartford Art School]], the [[The New School for Social Research|New School for Social Research]] and the [[University of California, Los Angeles]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/08/16/obituaries/fay-honey-knopp-dies-at-76-founded-quaker-prison-ministry.html|title=Fay Honey Knopp, Dies at 76; Founded Quaker Prison Ministry|last=Saxon|first=Wolfgang|date=1995-08-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 1939, she attended a Quaker peace demonstration as a Gandhian pacifist. In 1955, Knopp began visiting [[Conscientious objector|conscientious objectors]] of the [[Vietnam War]] in prison. In 1962, she traveled to Geneva, Switzerland as part of the [[Women Strike for Peace]] delegation, protesting the effects of nuclear testing on children's health. Also that year, Knopp became a Quaker serving as a prison visitor in the Federal penitentiary system through her designation as a \"minister of record\", and in 1968 co-founded [[Prisoner Visitation and Support]] with Bob Horton to further that work.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8XPcAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA636|title=The Oxford Handbook of Quaker Studies|last=Angell|first=Stephen Ward|last2=Angell|first2=Stephen W.|last3=Dandelion|first3=Pink|date=2013-09-26|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=9780199608676|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, she founded the Safer Society Program and was the director until 1993. The program's goal was to offer sex offenders treatment through an international referral system to break the cycle of behavior rather than punishment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/08/14/us/a-vermonter-s-tough-help-for-the-sex-abuser.html|title=A Vermonter's 'Tough' Help for the Sex Abuser|last=Johnson|first=Sally|date=1988-08-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-25|last2=Times|first2=Special to The New York|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> In 1976, Knopp founded the Prison Research Education Action Program and published the book ''Instead of Prisons: A Handbook for Abolitionists.'' The book includes three goals for abolitionists: prohibit the building of new prisons, reduce prison populations, and move away from [[Imprisonment|incarceration]] as a solution.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/17/magazine/prison-abolition-ruth-wilson-gilmore.html|title=Is Prison Necessary? Ruth Wilson Gilmore Might Change Your Mind|last=Kushner|first=Rachel|date=2019-04-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/what-is-prison-abolition/|title=What Is Prison Abolition?|last=Washington|first=John|date=2018-07-31|access-date=2019-06-25|language=en-US|issn=0027-8378}}</ref>\n\nShe was also director of the New York Region of the American Friends Service Committee, projects director for the National Peace Education Division in Philadelphia.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nKnopp died on August 10, 1995 in [[Shoreham, Vermont|Shoreham]], [[Vermont]] from [[ovarian cancer]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Reception ==\nMost academic criminologists, even those of an abolitionist persuasion, seem to have never heard of Fay Honey Knopp. Criminologist Harold E. Pepinsky mentions that he \"had never read her work or seen it cited in the criminological literatur\". He now thinks that \"she ought to be ranked as one of the giants in U.S. criminology...Her Quakerism, her radical feminism, and her prison abolitionism have reinforced and informed one another\" (<ref>Pepinsky, Harold E. ''Peacemaking in Criminology and Criminal Justice'' In: Pepinsky/Quinney, eds., Criminology as Peacemaking, Bloomington: Indiana University Press 1991, 314</ref>). Dutch criminologist [[Herman Bianchi]] remembers her as the \"Mother Teresa among abolitionists\" (<ref> Feest,Johannes, Definitionsmacht, Renitenz, Abolitionismus. Wiesbaden 2020, 299</ref>).\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* ''Instead of Prisons: A Handbook for Abolitionists'', 1976<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/insteadofprisons00knop|url-access=registration|title=Instead of Prisons: A Handbook for Abolitionists|last=Knopp|first=Fay Honey|last2=Boward|first2=Barbara|last3=Morris|first3=Mark|last4=Schnapper|first4=Morris Bartel|date=1976|publisher=Prison Research Education Action Project|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Retraining adult sex offenders: methods & models'', 1984<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XWVHAAAAMAAJ|title=Retraining adult sex offenders: methods & models|last=Knopp|first=Fay Honey|last2=Churches)|first2=Prison Research/Education/Action Project (New York State Council of|date=1984|publisher=Safer Society Press|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Community Solutions to Sexual Violence. Feminist/Abolitionist Perspectives''.<ref>Harold Pepinsky/Richard Quinney, eds., (1991) Criminology as Peacemaking,Bloomington: Indiana University Press, 181-193</ref>.\n*''When Your Wife Says No: Forced Sex in Marriage'', 1994<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OtsSAAAACAAJ|title=When Your Wife Says No: Forced Sex in Marriage|last=Knopp|first=Fay Honey|date=1994|publisher=Safer Society Press|isbn=9781884444104|language=en}}</ref>\n*''A primer on the complexities of traumatic memory of childhood sexual abuse: a psychobiological approach'', 1996<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RYRHAAAAMAAJ|title=A primer on the complexities of traumatic memory of childhood sexual abuse: a psychobiological approach|last=Knopp|first=Fay Honey|last2=Benson|first2=Anna Rose|date=1996|publisher=Safer Society Press|year=|isbn=9781884444203|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.prisonervisitation.org/ Prisoner Visitation and Support]\n* [https://www.safersociety.org Safer Society Program]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knopp, Fay Honey}}\n[[Category:Prison abolitionists]]\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "'''Fay \"Honey\" Knopp''' ({{nee}} '''Irving''', August 15, 1918 \u2013 August 10, 1995) was a [[Quakers|Quaker]] minister, peace and civil rights advocate, and [[Prison abolition movement|prison abolitionist]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nFay Birdie Irving was born on  August 15, 1918 in [[Bridgeport, Connecticut|Bridgeport]], [[Connecticut]] to Mollie Feldman and Alexander Ajolo Irving, a Russian-Jewish emigree. She graduated from [[Warren Harding High School]] as valedictorian in 1935. After high school, she became a women's fashion buyer and in 1941 married Burton Knopp. Together they had two children, Sari and Connecticut politician [[Alex Knopp]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WSaMu4F06AQC&pg=PA347|title=Notable American Women: A Biographical Dictionary Completing the Twentieth Century|last=Ware|first=Susan|date=2004|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=9780674014886|language=en}}</ref> She studied at the [[University of Hartford|Hartford Art School]], the [[The New School for Social Research|New School for Social Research]] and the [[University of California, Los Angeles]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/08/16/obituaries/fay-honey-knopp-dies-at-76-founded-quaker-prison-ministry.html|title=Fay Honey Knopp, Dies at 76; Founded Quaker Prison Ministry|last=Saxon|first=Wolfgang|date=1995-08-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 1939, she attended a Quaker peace demonstration as a Gandhian pacifist. In 1955, Knopp began visiting [[Conscientious objector|conscientious objectors]] of the [[Vietnam War]] in prison. In 1962, she traveled to Geneva, Switzerland as part of the [[Women Strike for Peace]] delegation, protesting the effects of nuclear testing on children's health. Also that year, Knopp became a Quaker serving as a prison visitor in the Federal penitentiary system through her designation as a \"minister of record\", and in 1968 co-founded [[Prisoner Visitation and Support]] with Bob Horton to further that work.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8XPcAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA636|title=The Oxford Handbook of Quaker Studies|last=Angell|first=Stephen Ward|last2=Angell|first2=Stephen W.|last3=Dandelion|first3=Pink|date=2013-09-26|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=9780199608676|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, she founded the Safer Society Program and was the director until 1993. The program's goal was to offer sex offenders treatment through an international referral system to break the cycle of behavior rather than punishment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/08/14/us/a-vermonter-s-tough-help-for-the-sex-abuser.html|title=A Vermonter's 'Tough' Help for the Sex Abuser|last=Johnson|first=Sally|date=1988-08-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-25|last2=Times|first2=Special to The New York|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> In 1976, Knopp founded the Prison Research Education Action Program and published the book ''Instead of Prisons: A Handbook for Abolitionists.'' The book includes three goals for abolitionists: prohibit the building of new prisons, reduce prison populations, and move away from [[Imprisonment|incarceration]] as a solution.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/17/magazine/prison-abolition-ruth-wilson-gilmore.html|title=Is Prison Necessary? Ruth Wilson Gilmore Might Change Your Mind|last=Kushner|first=Rachel|date=2019-04-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/what-is-prison-abolition/|title=What Is Prison Abolition?|last=Washington|first=John|date=2018-07-31|access-date=2019-06-25|language=en-US|issn=0027-8378}}</ref>\n\nShe was also director of the New York Region of the American Friends Service Committee, projects director for the National Peace Education Division in Philadelphia.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nKnopp died on August 10, 1995 in [[Shoreham, Vermont|Shoreham]], [[Vermont]] from [[ovarian cancer]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Reception ==\nMost academic riminologists, even those of an abolitionist persuasion, seem to have never heard of Fay Honey Knopp. Criminologist Harold E. Pepinsky mentions that he \"had never read her work or seen it cited in the criminological literatur\". He now thinks that \"she ought to be ranked as one of the giants in U.S. criminology...Her Quakerism, her radical feminism, and her prison abolitionism have reinforced and informed one another\" (<ref>Pepinsky, Harold E. ''Peacemaking in Criminology and Criminal Justice'' In: Pepinsky/Quinney, eds., Criminology as Peacemaking, Bloomington: Indiana University Press 1991, 314</ref>). Dutch criminologist [[Herman Bianchi]] remembers her as the \"Mother Teresa among abolitionists\" (<ref> Feest,Johannes, Definitionsmacht, Renitenz, Abolitionismus. Wiesbaden 2020, 299</ref>).\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* ''Instead of Prisons: A Handbook for Abolitionists'', 1976<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/insteadofprisons00knop|url-access=registration|title=Instead of Prisons: A Handbook for Abolitionists|last=Knopp|first=Fay Honey|last2=Boward|first2=Barbara|last3=Morris|first3=Mark|last4=Schnapper|first4=Morris Bartel|date=1976|publisher=Prison Research Education Action Project|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Retraining adult sex offenders: methods & models'', 1984<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XWVHAAAAMAAJ|title=Retraining adult sex offenders: methods & models|last=Knopp|first=Fay Honey|last2=Churches)|first2=Prison Research/Education/Action Project (New York State Council of|date=1984|publisher=Safer Society Press|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Community Solutions to Sexual Violence. Feminist/Abolitionist Perspectives''.<ref>Harold Pepinsky/Richard Quinney, eds., (1991) Criminology as Peacemaking,Bloomington: Indiana University Press, 181-193</ref>.\n*''When Your Wife Says No: Forced Sex in Marriage'', 1994<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OtsSAAAACAAJ|title=When Your Wife Says No: Forced Sex in Marriage|last=Knopp|first=Fay Honey|date=1994|publisher=Safer Society Press|isbn=9781884444104|language=en}}</ref>\n*''A primer on the complexities of traumatic memory of childhood sexual abuse: a psychobiological approach'', 1996<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RYRHAAAAMAAJ|title=A primer on the complexities of traumatic memory of childhood sexual abuse: a psychobiological approach|last=Knopp|first=Fay Honey|last2=Benson|first2=Anna Rose|date=1996|publisher=Safer Society Press|year=|isbn=9781884444203|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.prisonervisitation.org/ Prisoner Visitation and Support]\n* [https://www.safersociety.org Safer Society Program]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knopp, Fay Honey}}\n[[Category:Prison abolitionists]]\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Johann Nepomuk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReception", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fay_Honey_Knopp"}
{"title_page": "Yoake Made Tsuyogaranakutemoii", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 single by Nogizaka46}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Yoake Made Tsuyogaranakutemoii\n| cover      = Yoake Made Tsuyogaranakutemoii Type A.jpeg\n| alt        = Type A cover\n| caption    = Type A cover\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Nogizaka46]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = {{Plainlist|\n*\"Boku no Koto, Shitteru?\" (Common)\n*\"Romendensha no Machi\" (Type-A)\n*\"Toshoshitsu no Kimi e\" (Type-B)\n*\"Tokidoki Omoidashite Kudasai\" (Type-C)\n*\"~Do my best~ Ja Imi wa Nai\" (Type-D)\n*\"Boku no Omoikomi\" (Regular)}}\n| released   = {{Start date|df=y|2019|09|04}} (Japan)\n| format     = [[CD single]], [[Music download|digital download]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[J-pop]]\n| length     = \n| label      = [[Sony Music Records#Labels and sublabels|N46Div.]]\n| composer   =\n| lyricist   =\n| producer   = [[Yasushi Akimoto]]\n| prev_title = [[Sing Out! (song)|Sing Out!]]\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| next_title = [[Shiawase no Hogoshoku]]\n| next_year  = 2020\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|9yCEYQeMqJc|\"Yoake Made Tsuyogaranakutemoii\"|link=no}}}}\n}}\n{{nihongo|\"'''Yoake Made Tsuyogaranakutemoii'''\"|\u591c\u660e\u3051\u307e\u3067\u5f37\u304c\u3089\u306a\u304f\u3066\u3082\u3044\u3044}} is the 24th single by [[Japanese idol]] group [[Nogizaka46]]. The single was released on 4 September 2019. It reached [[List of Oricon number-one singles of 2019|number-one]] on the weekly [[Oricon Singles Chart]] and remained on the chart for twenty-four weeks.<ref name=\"oricon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/prof/556578/products/1331167/1/|title=\u591c\u660e\u3051\u307e\u3067\u5f37\u304c\u3089\u306a\u304f\u3066\u3082\u3044\u3044(TYPE-A)|publisher=[[Oricon]]|accessdate=February 19, 2020|language=Japanese}}</ref>\nAdditionally, the single was also [[List of Hot 100 number-one singles of 2019 (Japan)|number-one]] on the [[Billboard Japan Hot 100]].<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard-japan.com/charts/detail?a=hot100&year=2019&month=09&day=16|title=Billboard Japan Hot 100 2019/09/16|work=[[Billboard Japan]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe center position of the title track is held by Sakura Endo, a fourth generation member; additionally, two other fourth generation members, Haruka Kaki and Ayame Tsutsui, were placed in the first row.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u300124th\u30b7\u30f3\u30b0\u30eb\u30bb\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u306f4\u671f\u751f\u30fb\u9060\u85e4\u3055\u304f\u3089\u3000\u9078\u629c18\u540d\u767a\u8868 |url=https://mdpr.jp/news/detail/1851541 |accessdate=February 19, 2020 |agency=Modelpress |date=July 15, 2019 |language=ja}}</ref> This single marks the first time a fourth generation member participated in a title track or held a center position.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b7\u30f3\u30b0\u30eb\u306b\u685c\u4e95\u73b2\u9999\u6700\u521d\u3067\u6700\u5f8c\u306e\u30bd\u30ed\u66f2 |url=https://natalie.mu/music/news/341914 |website=[[Natalie (website)|Natalie]] |accessdate=February 19, 2020 |language=ja |date=July 31, 2019}}</ref> It is also the last single that former captain [[Reika Sakurai]] participated in.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u4e43\u6728\u574246\u9f4b\u85e4\u98db\u9ce5\uff06\u767d\u77f3\u9ebb\u8863\u304c\u8a9e\u308b\u65b0\u30bb\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u30fb\u9060\u85e4\u3055\u304f\u3089\u3078\u306e\u601d\u3044\u300e\u591c\u660e\u3051\u307e\u3067\u5f37\u304c\u3089\u306a\u304f\u3066\u3082\u3044\u3044\u300f\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc |url=https://times.abema.tv/posts/7018295 |website=Abema Times |publisher=[[AbemaTV]] |accessdate=February 19, 2020 |language=ja |date=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nThis single was released in 5 versions. Type-A, Type-B, Type-C, Type-D and a regular edition.\n\n==Track listing==\nAll lyrics written by [[Yasushi Akimoto]].\n\n=== Type-A<