 The Door\"\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[American Dad!]]''\n|Himself (voice)\n|Episode: \"Introducing The Naughty Stewardesses\"\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Bad Teacher (TV series)|Bad Teacher]]''\n|Himself\n|Episode: \"Fieldtrippers\"\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[The League]]''\n|Himself\n|Episode: \"The Height Supremacist\"\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Cristela]]''\n|Himself\n|Episode: \"Super Fan\"\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Girl Meets World]]''\n|Himself\n|Episode: \"Girl Meets Money\"\n|-\n|2017 \n|''[[Fast N' Loud]]'' \n|Himself \n|Episode: \"100 Monkeys\"\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Billions (TV series)|Billions]]''\n|Himself\n|Episode: \"The Oath\"\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Bar Rescue]]''\n|Himself\n|Episode: \"Operation: Puerto Rico\"\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Billions (TV series)|Billions]]''\n|Himself\n|Episode: \"Extreme Sandbox\"\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[The Rookie (TV series)|The Rookie]]''\n|Himself\n|Episode: \"Impact\"\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Grace and Frankie]]''\n|Himself\n|Episode: \"The Tank\"\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Brooklyn Nine-Nine]]''\n|Himself\n|Episode: \"The Takeback\"\n|}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Div col end}}\n*''How to Win at the Sport of Business: If I Can Do It, You Can Do It''. Diversion Publishing. 2011. {{ISBN|978-1626810914}}\n*''Let's Go, Mavs!.'' [[Mascot Books]]. 2007. {{ISBN|978-1932888720}}<ref>{{Cite book|title=Let's go, Mavs! Starring Champ and Cort the Sport|last=Cuban|first=Mark|date=2007|publisher=[[Mascot Books]]|others=De Angel, Miguel., Perez, Gerry., Aryal, Aimee.|isbn=9781932888720|location=Herndon, Va.|pages=|oclc=840122016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Mark Cuban}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.blogmaverick.com/ Blog]\n*{{C-SPAN|markcuban}}\n*{{IMDb name|1171860}}\n*{{NYTtopic|people/c/mark_cuban}}\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/mark-cuban Mark Cuban] collected news and commentary at ''[[The Guardian]]''\n\n{{Dallas Mavericks}}\n{{NBAOwners}}\n{{Shark Tank}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Sports}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cuban, Mark}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:2929 Entertainment holdings]]\n[[Category:American activists]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:American male bloggers]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American book publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:American business writers]]\n[[Category:American chairmen of corporations]]\n[[Category:American children's writers]]\n[[Category:American computer businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American corporate directors]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American financiers]]\n[[Category:American investors]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:American mass media owners]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Romanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American reality television producers]]\n[[Category:American retail chief executives]]\n[[Category:American salespeople]]\n[[Category:American technology chief executives]]\n[[Category:American technology company founders]]\n[[Category:American technology writers]]\n[[Category:American television company founders]]\n[[Category:American television executives]]\n[[Category:American venture capitalists]]\n[[Category:American bartenders]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Texas]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in information technology]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in software]]\n[[Category:Copyright activists]]\n[[Category:Dallas Mavericks owners]]\n[[Category:Esports people]]\n[[Category:Jewish activists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Kelley School of Business alumni]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:People from Mt. Lebanon, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Dallas]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Texas Independents]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Dallas]]\n[[Category:Writers from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Writers from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Television producers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Television producers from Texas]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Texas]]\n", "name_user": "108.30.156.186", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Cuban"}
{"title_page": "This is Not My Hat", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name = This Is Not My Hat\n| image = Image:Klassen_This_Is_Not_My_Hat_cover.jpg\n| caption = front cover of unknown edition\n| author = [[Jon Klassen]]\n| illustrator = Jon Klassen\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| genre = [[Picture book|Children's picture book]]\n| publisher = [[Candlewick Press]]\n| release_date = [[2012 in literature|2012]]\n| media_type = Print ([[hardback]] & [[paperback]])\n| pages = 40 pp\n| isbn = 9780763655990\n| oclc = 779856963\n}}\n\n'''''This Is Not My Hat''''' is a 2012 [[Children's literature|children's]] [[picture book]] by the author and illustrator [[Jon Klassen]]. The story is told through the [[unreliable narrator|unreliable narration]] of a little fish, who has stolen a hat from a big fish and how the big fish reacts to the theft. It is a thematic follow-up to ''[[I Want My Hat Back]]'' and was meant to be a more literal sequel until Klassen took a suggestion to change which animals were in the story. The book was well received by critics who praised its dark or ironic humor which could only be understood by comparing the words of the little fish's narration against the events of the illustrations. In addition to several positive reviews, Klassen won the 2013 [[Caldecott Medal]] and the 2014 [[Kate Greenaway Medal]] becoming the first book to win both awards. ''This is Not My Hat'' was also a commercial success. \n\n== Background and publication ==\n[[File:Jon Klassen 2013.jpg|alt=<nowiki>picture of Jon Klassen</nowiki>|left|thumb|Klassen in 2013.]]\nFollowing the success of ''[[I Want My Hat Back]]'', Klassen attempted unsuccessfully to tell more stories with the same characters, until the art director at his publisher, [[Candlewick Press]], suggested he try new characters instead.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://100scopenotes.com/2012/10/09/psycoanalyzing-jon-klassen/|title=Psychoanalyzing Jon Klassen \u2014 @100scopenotes 100 Scope Notes|last=Jonker|first=Travis|date=2012-10-09|website=100scopenotes.com|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> Klassen then switched from mammals to fish.<ref name=\":7\" /> Klassen also felt that this story was more \"dramatic\" than his earlier work and cited the \"[[The Tell-Tale Heart]]\" as a thematic inspiration.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/books/la-xpm-2012-oct-07-la-jc-kids-book-author-jon-klassen-talks-about-this-is-not-my-hat-20121005-story.html|title=Kids' book author Jon Klassen discusses 'This is Not My Hat'|date=2012-10-07|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2019-03-22|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/gallery/2014/jun/23/jon-klassen-this-is-not-my-hat-kate-greenaway-in-pictures|title=Jon Klassen: Kate Greenaway medal winner 2014 \u2013 in pictures|last=Drabble|first=Emily|date=2014-06-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-22|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> For this book he sketched the illustrations in ink before digitizing them and finishing the colors and details electronically.<ref name=\":11\" /> \n\nThe book was published on October 9, 2012, and was translated into more than 22 languages.<ref name=\":9\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/jon-klassen/not-my-hat/|title=This Is Not My Hat|date=29 August 2015|magazine=[[Kirkus Reviews]]|publisher=Kirkus Media LLC|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/childrens/childrens-book-news/article/61796-klassen-s-hat-books-hit-one-million-mark.html|title=Klassen's 'Hat' Books Hit One-Million Mark|last=Lodge|first=Sally|date=2014-08-10|magazine=[[Publishers Weekly]]|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> Klassen toured 15 cities in the United States to promote the book.<ref name=\":8\" /> In 2014 an audiobook read by John Keating and accompanied by string instruments to represent the actions of the fish, in a way similar to the orchestration of [[Peter and the Wolf]], was released.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Taylor|first=L.|year=2014|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A373034874/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=8b5c429f|title= Klassen, Jon. ''This Is Not My Hat ''|journal=[[School Library Journal]]|volume=60|issue=7|page=49}}</ref>\n\nIn October of 2019, Candlewick Press released a boxed set featuring ''This is Not My Hat'' along with its two companion books (''[[I Want My Hat Back]]'' and ''[[We Found a Hat]]''), calling it ''Jon Klassen\u2019s Hat Box''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43671840-jon-klassen-s-hat-box|title=Jon Klassen's Hat Box|last=|first=|date=|website=Goodreads|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nA small fish has stolen a hat from a big sleeping fish, and boasts about how easy it will be for him to get away with the theft, because the big fish will not wake up any time soon and maybe not even not notice the missing hat, or know who stole it, or where the small fish is going. Except the big fish does wake up and does notice. The little fish goes to hide in some plants, and is observed by a crab who tells the big fish, who follows the little fish. The little fish remains convinced that the theft will not be found out, but at the end of the story the big fish is wearing the hat.\n\n== Writing and illustrations ==\nAs Roger Sutton noted in his review of the book for ''[[The New York Times]]'', the book can only be understood by weighing the words against the actions depicted in the illustrations,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/11/books/review/little-tug-and-this-is-not-my-hat.html|title=\u2018Little Tug\u2019 and \u2018This Is Not My Hat\u2019|last=Sutton|first=Roger|date=2012-11-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-20|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> since what happens at the end is not explicitly stated but instead left to the reader to figure out.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hbook.com/2012/09/blogs/calling-caldecott/this-is-not-my-hat/|title=This Is Not My Hat \u2014 The Horn Book|last=Robinson|first=Lolly|date=2012-09-07|website=www.hbook.com|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref><ref name=\":12\" /> The small fish, acting as the book's narrator through its monologue, is not only amoral but also \"outrageous\" in the claims that it will not get caught.<ref name=\":2\" /> The small fish can be seen as either talking to the reader or themselves.<ref>Goodwin, P. (2013, Summer). Klassen, Jon: [http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A336603857/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=cc83a55d This is Not My Hat]. ''School Librarian'', ''61''(2), 92. Retrieved from Gale.</ref> The book presents a complex ethical message, with an amoral narrator.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> ''This is Not My Hat'' suggests both not to steal but that if you do steal not to get caught.<ref name=\":1\" /> The reader can both cheer for the little fish's escape and for the little fish to be punished for the theft.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.commonsensemedia.org/book-reviews/this-is-not-my-hat|title=This Is Not My Hat|website=www.commonsensemedia.org|publisher=Common Sense Media Inc.|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref> The book was part of a trend of authors and illustrators exploring \"meta\" issues in children's picture books.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hbook.com/2013/01/blogs/calling-caldecott/on-ethics-food-chains-and-this-is-not-my-hat/|title=Ethics, food chains, and stolen hats \u2014 The Horn Book|last=Robinson|first=Lolly|date=2013-01-31|website=www.hbook.com|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> Critics wondered if the book's success was a sign that young children were able to pick up on ironic humor<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/pageviews/not-hat-reading-2013-caldecott-winner-blog-entry-1.1639829|title='This is Not My Hat': Reading (a little) too much into the 2013 Caldecott winner|last=Le|first=Minh|date=2013-01-30|website=nydailynews.com|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> and if the dark message was a sign of the general American mood.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":6\" />\n\nThe book was praised for its design<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.booklistonline.com/This-Is-Not-My-Hat-Jon-Klassen/pid=5498353|title=This Is Not My Hat, by Jon Klassen {{!}} Booklist Online|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|publication-date=2012-08-01|pages=|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> and simplicity.<ref name=\":14\" /> Some reviewers noted Klassen's felicity with using colors like black and brown in the illustrations.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\">Smith, R. L. (2012). [http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=lkh&AN=79320293&site=lrc-plus This Is Not My Hat.] ''Horn Book Magazine'', ''88''(5), 66\u201367. Retrieved from ebscohost.</ref> The perspective of the illustrations also never changes staying roughly in a [[medium shot]].<ref name=\":2\" /> The feelings of the characters is expressed almost entirely through their eye movements.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The illustrations were compared to those of [[Leo Lionni]].<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n==Reception and awards==\n''This is Not My Hat'' received favorable reviews including several [[starred reviews]]. In its starred review ''[[Booklist]]'' praised the book's humor and noted its \"suggestively dark conclusion\",<ref name=\":13\" /> ''[[The Bulletin of the Center for Children's Books]]''  called the book \"quite simply, an outstanding book\", and ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' wrote that, \"Klassen excels at using pictures to tell the parts of the story his unreliable narrators omit or evade\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-7636-5599-0|title=This Is Not My Hat|website=www.publishersweekly.com|publisher=PWxyz LLC|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref> ''[[The Horn Book Magazine]]''<ref name=\":3\" /> and ''[[School Library Journal]]'' also awarded the book starred reviews.<ref name=\":14\">{{cite web|url=https://www.slj.com/?reviewDetail=this-is-not-my-hat|title=Pick of the Day: This Is Not My Hat|date=24 September 2012|website=www.slj.com|publisher=Media Source Inc|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref>  In a \"highly recommend\" review for ''Library Media Connection'' librarian Lisa Wright writes, \"The narrative parallels the illustrations as the reader deduces the facts of the actual theft.\"<ref name=\":12\">Wright, L. (2013). [http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=lkh&AN=84557877&site=lrc-plus This Is Not My Hat]. ''Library Media Connection'', ''31''(4), 63. Retrieved from ebscohost.</ref> In a review for ''The New York Times'' children's literature expert Roger Sutton notes that the action and illustrations mean not all young children will be old enough to understand and appreciate the book.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nThe book spent more than forty weeks on [[The New York Times Best Seller list]] and the combined sales of it and ''I Want My Hat Back'' were more than 1.5 million copies.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/childrens/childrens-book-news/article/69066-jon-klassen-scores-a-hat-trick.html|title=Jon Klassen Scores a Hat Trick|last=Lodge|first=Sally|date=2016-01-05|website=www.publishersweekly.com|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> The book appeared on several best of children's books of 2012 lists including Publisher's Weekly<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://best-books.publishersweekly.com/pw/best-books/2012/childrens-picture|title=Best Books of 2012 {{!}} Publishers Weekly Publishers Weekly|website=PublishersWeekly.com|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> and ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/gallery/10-great-kids-books-2012/|title=10 Great Kids Books of 2012|last=Fowler|first=Tara|last2=Stillman|first2=Josh|date=2012-12-27|website=EW.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> \n\n''This is Not My Hat'' was the winner of the 2013 [[Caldecott Medal]] and Klassen was also awarded with a Caldecott Honor the same year for ''[[Extra Yarn]]'', only the second time that has happened.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/alsc/2013-caldecott-medal-and-honor-books|title=2013 Caldecott Medal and Honor Books|website=Association for Library Service to Children (ALSC)|language=en|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hbook.com/2013/01/blogs/calling-caldecott/caldecott-2013-post-mortem/|title=Caldecott 2013 post mortem \u2014 The Horn Book|last=Robinson|first=Lolly|date=2013-01-29|website=www.hbook.com|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> Caldecott Chair Sandra Imdieke praised the book's illustrations: \u201cWith minute changes in eyes and the slightest displacement of seagrass, Klassen\u2019s masterful illustrations tell the story the narrator doesn\u2019t know.\u201d<ref name=\":4\" /> Klassen found out as he was about to get in an early morning cab to fly to California.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2013/01/29/jon-klassen-this-is-not-my-hat-caldecott-medal-interview-exclusive/|title='This Is Not My Hat' author Jon Klassen on his Caldecott Medal win: 'I feel like I'm going to get hit by a bus' -- EXCLUSIVE|last=Fowler|first=Tara|date=2013-01-29|website=EW.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> Klassen was surprised by his win and tried not to think about it, saying, \"It\u2019s such a prestigious award that the idea of winning one is pretty easy to put out of your head.\"<ref name=\":5\" /> ''This is Not My Hat'' was also the recipient of the 2014 [[Kate Greenaway Medal]]. Klassen is the first person to win both the Greenaway and Caldecott awards for the same work.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Diaz|first=Shelley|date=2014-06-26|title=Klassen and Brooks Take UK\u2019s Greenaway and Carnegie Medals|url=http://www.slj.com/2014/06/industry-news/klassen-and-brooks-take-uks-greenaway-and-carnegie-medals/#_|journal=School Library Journal|publisher=Media Source Inc.|volume=|pages=|accessdate=2016-12-23|quote=Klassen is the first Canadian and his title is the first Caldecott Medal-winning book to win the Greenaway.|via=}}</ref>{{efn|Publication year for the British CILIP awards is the school year, roughly, September 2012 to August 2013 for consideration in 2014. Publication year for the American Library Association awards is the preceding calendar year. The ALA considers only picture books published first in the United States for the Caldecott Medal. CILIP considers all illustrated children's books for the Greenaway and its judges recommended the eight books on its 2014 shortlist for children as old as ages 9+.}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|ZlzbpXFGzXU|''This Is Not My Hat}}\n* {{Vimeo|36749324|''This Is Not My Hat/I Want My Hat Back-First Edition}}\n{{Portal |Children's literature}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Caldecott Medal|Caldecott Medal recipient]]|before=''[[A Ball for Daisy]]''|after=''[[Locomotive (book)|Locomotive]]''|years=[[2013 in literature|2013]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n[[Category:2012 children's books]]\n[[Category:Caldecott Medal-winning works]]\n[[Category:Kate Greenaway Medal winning works]]\n[[Category:Fictional fish]]\n[[Category:American children's books]]\n[[Category:American picture books]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name = This Is Not My Hat\n| image = Image:Klassen_This_Is_Not_My_Hat_cover.jpg\n| caption = front cover of unknown edition\n| author = [[Jon Klassen]]\n| illustrator = Jon Klassen\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| genre = [[Picture book|Children's picture book]]\n| publisher = [[Candlewick Press]]\n| release_date = [[2012 in literature|2012]]\n| media_type = Print ([[hardback]] & [[paperback]])\n| pages = 40 pp\n| isbn = 9780763655990\n| oclc = 779856963\n}}\n\n'''''This Is Not My Hat''''' is a 2012 [[Children's literature|children's]] [[picture book]] by the author and illustrator [[Jon Klassen]]. The story is told through the [[unreliable narrator|unreliable narration]] of a little fish, who has stolen a hat from a big fish and how the big fish reacts to the theft. It is a thematic follow-up to ''[[I Want My Hat Back]]'' and was meant to be a more literal sequel until Klassen took a suggestion to change which animals were in the story. The book was well received by critics who praised its dark or ironic humor which could only be understood by comparing the words of the little fish's narration against the events of the illustrations. In addition to several positive reviews, Klassen won the 2013 [[Caldecott Medal]] and the 2014 [[Kate Greenaway Medal]] becoming the first book to win both awards. ''This is Not My Hat'' was also a commercial success. \n\n== Background and publication ==\n[[File:Jon Klassen 2013.jpg|alt=<nowiki>picture of Jon Klassen</nowiki>|left|thumb|Klassen in 2013.]]\nFollowing the success of ''[[I Want My Hat Back]]'', Klassen attempted unsuccessfully to tell more stories with the same characters, until the art director at his publisher, [[Candlewick Press]], suggested he try new characters instead.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://100scopenotes.com/2012/10/09/psycoanalyzing-jon-klassen/|title=Psychoanalyzing Jon Klassen \u2014 @100scopenotes 100 Scope Notes|last=Jonker|first=Travis|date=2012-10-09|website=100scopenotes.com|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> Klassen then switched from mammals to fish.<ref name=\":7\" /> Klassen also felt that this story was more \"dramatic\" than his earlier work and cited the \"[[The Tell-Tale Heart]]\" as a thematic inspiration.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/books/la-xpm-2012-oct-07-la-jc-kids-book-author-jon-klassen-talks-about-this-is-not-my-hat-20121005-story.html|title=Kids' book author Jon Klassen discusses 'This is Not My Hat'|date=2012-10-07|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2019-03-22|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/gallery/2014/jun/23/jon-klassen-this-is-not-my-hat-kate-greenaway-in-pictures|title=Jon Klassen: Kate Greenaway medal winner 2014 \u2013 in pictures|last=Drabble|first=Emily|date=2014-06-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-22|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> For this book he sketched the illustrations in ink before digitizing them and finishing the colors and details electronically.<ref name=\":11\" /> \n\nThe book was published on October 9, 2012, and was translated into more than 22 languages.<ref name=\":9\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/jon-klassen/not-my-hat/|title=This Is Not My Hat|date=29 August 2015|magazine=[[Kirkus Reviews]]|publisher=Kirkus Media LLC|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/childrens/childrens-book-news/article/61796-klassen-s-hat-books-hit-one-million-mark.html|title=Klassen's 'Hat' Books Hit One-Million Mark|last=Lodge|first=Sally|date=2014-08-10|magazine=[[Publishers Weekly]]|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> Klassen toured 15 cities in the United States to promote the book.<ref name=\":8\" /> In 2014 an audiobook read by John Keating and accompanied by string instruments to represent the actions of the fish, in a way similar to the orchestration of [[Peter and the Wolf]], was released.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Taylor|first=L.|year=2014|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A373034874/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=8b5c429f|title= Klassen, Jon. ''This Is Not My Hat ''|journal=[[School Library Journal]]|volume=60|issue=7|page=49}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nA small fish has stolen a hat from a big sleeping fish, and boasts about how easy it will be for him to get away with the theft, because the big fish will not wake up any time soon and maybe not even not notice the missing hat, or know who stole it, or where the small fish is going. Except the big fish does wake up and does notice. The little fish goes to hide in some plants, and is observed by a crab who tells the big fish, who follows the little fish. The little fish remains convinced that the theft will not be found out, but at the end of the story the big fish is wearing the hat.\n\n== Writing and illustrations ==\nAs Roger Sutton noted in his review of the book for ''[[The New York Times]]'', the book can only be understood by weighing the words against the actions depicted in the illustrations,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/11/books/review/little-tug-and-this-is-not-my-hat.html|title=\u2018Little Tug\u2019 and \u2018This Is Not My Hat\u2019|last=Sutton|first=Roger|date=2012-11-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-20|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> since what happens at the end is not explicitly stated but instead left to the reader to figure out.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hbook.com/2012/09/blogs/calling-caldecott/this-is-not-my-hat/|title=This Is Not My Hat \u2014 The Horn Book|last=Robinson|first=Lolly|date=2012-09-07|website=www.hbook.com|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref><ref name=\":12\" /> The small fish, acting as the book's narrator through its monologue, is not only amoral but also \"outrageous\" in the claims that it will not get caught.<ref name=\":2\" /> The small fish can be seen as either talking to the reader or themselves.<ref>Goodwin, P. (2013, Summer). Klassen, Jon: [http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A336603857/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=cc83a55d This is Not My Hat]. ''School Librarian'', ''61''(2), 92. Retrieved from Gale.</ref> The book presents a complex ethical message, with an amoral narrator.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> ''This is Not My Hat'' suggests both not to steal but that if you do steal not to get caught.<ref name=\":1\" /> The reader can both cheer for the little fish's escape and for the little fish to be punished for the theft.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.commonsensemedia.org/book-reviews/this-is-not-my-hat|title=This Is Not My Hat|website=www.commonsensemedia.org|publisher=Common Sense Media Inc.|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref> The book was part of a trend of authors and illustrators exploring \"meta\" issues in children's picture books.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hbook.com/2013/01/blogs/calling-caldecott/on-ethics-food-chains-and-this-is-not-my-hat/|title=Ethics, food chains, and stolen hats \u2014 The Horn Book|last=Robinson|first=Lolly|date=2013-01-31|website=www.hbook.com|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> Critics wondered if the book's success was a sign that young children were able to pick up on ironic humor<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/pageviews/not-hat-reading-2013-caldecott-winner-blog-entry-1.1639829|title='This is Not My Hat': Reading (a little) too much into the 2013 Caldecott winner|last=Le|first=Minh|date=2013-01-30|website=nydailynews.com|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> and if the dark message was a sign of the general American mood.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":6\" />\n\nThe book was praised for its design<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.booklistonline.com/This-Is-Not-My-Hat-Jon-Klassen/pid=5498353|title=This Is Not My Hat, by Jon Klassen {{!}} Booklist Online|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|publication-date=2012-08-01|pages=|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> and simplicity.<ref name=\":14\" /> Some reviewers noted Klassen's felicity with using colors like black and brown in the illustrations.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\">Smith, R. L. (2012). [http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=lkh&AN=79320293&site=lrc-plus This Is Not My Hat.] ''Horn Book Magazine'', ''88''(5), 66\u201367. Retrieved from ebscohost.</ref> The perspective of the illustrations also never changes staying roughly in a [[medium shot]].<ref name=\":2\" /> The feelings of the characters is expressed almost entirely through their eye movements.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The illustrations were compared to those of [[Leo Lionni]].<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n==Reception and awards==\n''This is Not My Hat'' received favorable reviews including several [[starred reviews]]. In its starred review ''[[Booklist]]'' praised the book's humor and noted its \"suggestively dark conclusion\",<ref name=\":13\" /> ''[[The Bulletin of the Center for Children's Books]]''  called the book \"quite simply, an outstanding book\", and ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' wrote that, \"Klassen excels at using pictures to tell the parts of the story his unreliable narrators omit or evade\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-7636-5599-0|title=This Is Not My Hat|website=www.publishersweekly.com|publisher=PWxyz LLC|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref> ''[[The Horn Book Magazine]]''<ref name=\":3\" /> and ''[[School Library Journal]]'' also awarded the book starred reviews.<ref name=\":14\">{{cite web|url=https://www.slj.com/?reviewDetail=this-is-not-my-hat|title=Pick of the Day: This Is Not My Hat|date=24 September 2012|website=www.slj.com|publisher=Media Source Inc|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref>  In a \"highly recommend\" review for ''Library Media Connection'' librarian Lisa Wright writes, \"The narrative parallels the illustrations as the reader deduces the facts of the actual theft.\"<ref name=\":12\">Wright, L. (2013). [http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=lkh&AN=84557877&site=lrc-plus This Is Not My Hat]. ''Library Media Connection'', ''31''(4), 63. Retrieved from ebscohost.</ref> In a review for ''The New York Times'' children's literature expert Roger Sutton notes that the action and illustrations mean not all young children will be old enough to understand and appreciate the book.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nThe book spent more than forty weeks on [[The New York Times Best Seller list]] and the combined sales of it and ''I Want My Hat Back'' were more than 1.5 million copies.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/childrens/childrens-book-news/article/69066-jon-klassen-scores-a-hat-trick.html|title=Jon Klassen Scores a Hat Trick|last=Lodge|first=Sally|date=2016-01-05|website=www.publishersweekly.com|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> The book appeared on several best of children's books of 2012 lists including Publisher's Weekly<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://best-books.publishersweekly.com/pw/best-books/2012/childrens-picture|title=Best Books of 2012 {{!}} Publishers Weekly Publishers Weekly|website=PublishersWeekly.com|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> and ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/gallery/10-great-kids-books-2012/|title=10 Great Kids Books of 2012|last=Fowler|first=Tara|last2=Stillman|first2=Josh|date=2012-12-27|website=EW.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> \n\n''This is Not My Hat'' was the winner of the 2013 [[Caldecott Medal]] and Klassen was also awarded with a Caldecott Honor the same year for ''[[Extra Yarn]]'', only the second time that has happened.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/alsc/2013-caldecott-medal-and-honor-books|title=2013 Caldecott Medal and Honor Books|website=Association for Library Service to Children (ALSC)|language=en|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hbook.com/2013/01/blogs/calling-caldecott/caldecott-2013-post-mortem/|title=Caldecott 2013 post mortem \u2014 The Horn Book|last=Robinson|first=Lolly|date=2013-01-29|website=www.hbook.com|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> Caldecott Chair Sandra Imdieke praised the book's illustrations: \u201cWith minute changes in eyes and the slightest displacement of seagrass, Klassen\u2019s masterful illustrations tell the story the narrator doesn\u2019t know.\u201d<ref name=\":4\" /> Klassen found out as he was about to get in an early morning cab to fly to California.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2013/01/29/jon-klassen-this-is-not-my-hat-caldecott-medal-interview-exclusive/|title='This Is Not My Hat' author Jon Klassen on his Caldecott Medal win: 'I feel like I'm going to get hit by a bus' -- EXCLUSIVE|last=Fowler|first=Tara|date=2013-01-29|website=EW.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> Klassen was surprised by his win and tried not to think about it, saying, \"It\u2019s such a prestigious award that the idea of winning one is pretty easy to put out of your head.\"<ref name=\":5\" /> ''This is Not My Hat'' was also the recipient of the 2014 [[Kate Greenaway Medal]]. Klassen is the first person to win both the Greenaway and Caldecott awards for the same work.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Diaz|first=Shelley|date=2014-06-26|title=Klassen and Brooks Take UK\u2019s Greenaway and Carnegie Medals|url=http://www.slj.com/2014/06/industry-news/klassen-and-brooks-take-uks-greenaway-and-carnegie-medals/#_|journal=School Library Journal|publisher=Media Source Inc.|volume=|pages=|accessdate=2016-12-23|quote=Klassen is the first Canadian and his title is the first Caldecott Medal-winning book to win the Greenaway.|via=}}</ref>{{efn|Publication year for the British CILIP awards is the school year, roughly, September 2012 to August 2013 for consideration in 2014. Publication year for the American Library Association awards is the preceding calendar year. The ALA considers only picture books published first in the United States for the Caldecott Medal. CILIP considers all illustrated children's books for the Greenaway and its judges recommended the eight books on its 2014 shortlist for children as old as ages 9+.}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|ZlzbpXFGzXU|''This Is Not My Hat}}\n* {{Vimeo|36749324|''This Is Not My Hat/I Want My Hat Back-First Edition}}\n{{Portal |Children's literature}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Caldecott Medal|Caldecott Medal recipient]]|before=''[[A Ball for Daisy]]''|after=''[[Locomotive (book)|Locomotive]]''|years=[[2013 in literature|2013]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n[[Category:2012 children's books]]\n[[Category:Caldecott Medal-winning works]]\n[[Category:Kate Greenaway Medal winning works]]\n[[Category:Fictional fish]]\n[[Category:American children's books]]\n[[Category:American picture books]]\n", "name_user": "KarlenP", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added info about subsequent publication", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/This_is_Not_My_Hat"}
{"title_page": "Lee Dong-hwi", "text_new": "{{short description|South Korean actor}}\n{{Distinguish|Yi Dong-hwi}}\n{{Korean name|Lee}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Lee Dong-hwi\n| image           = [[File:160305 \uc751\ub2f5\ud558\ub77c 1988 \ucf58\uc11c\ud2b8 \uc774\ub3d9\ud718 (Lee Dong Hwi) cropped.jpg|center|frameless]]\n| image_size      = \n| caption         = At ''[[Reply 1988]]'' concert in March 2015 \n| birth_name      = \n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1985|7|22}}\n| birth_place     = [[South Korea]]\n| occupation      = [[Actor]]\n| years_active    = \n| agent           = [[Huayi Brothers (South Korean company)|Huayi Brothers]]<br><small>(formerly Sim Entertainment)</small>\n| module          = {{Infobox Korean name|child=yes\n| hangul       = {{linktext|\uc774|\ub3d9|\ud718}}\n| hanja        = !\n| rr           = I Dong-hwi\n| mr           = Yi Tong-hwi\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Lee Dong-hwi''' (born July 22, 1985), is a South Korean actor. He gained recognition through his role in the Korean drama ''[[Reply 1988]]'' (2015\u20132016), the third installment of the ''[[Reply (TV series)|Reply]]'' series by [[TVN (South Korea)|tvN]].<ref>{{cite web|title=''Reply 1988'' Confirms 8 Actors in Cast Including Girl\u2032s Day\u2032s Hyeri, Ko Kyung Pyo, Park Bo Gum and More|url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/92738/reply-1988-confirms-8-actors-in-cast-including-girls-days-hyeri-ko-kyung-pyo-park-bo-gum-and-more|website=enewsWorld|accessdate=2015-09-08|date=18 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151008024405/http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/92738/reply-1988-confirms-8-actors-in-cast-including-girls-days-hyeri-ko-kyung-pyo-park-bo-gum-and-more|archive-date=8 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nThe actor's relationship with model Jung Ho-yeon was confirmed in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Actor Lee Dong Hwi and Model Jung Ho Yeon Revealed to Be Dating|url=http://www.soompi.com/2016/01/05/actor-lee-dong-hwi-and-model-jung-ho-yeon-revealed-to-be-dating/|website=Soompi}}</ref>\n\nHe is part of a celebrity group of friends known as BYH48 which consists of [[Exo (band)|EXO]]'s [[Suho]], [[Ryu Jun-yeol]], [[Byun Yo-han]], [[Ji Soo]] and more. The name was coined by their fans, with BYH referring to Byun Yo-han - the group's leader - and 48 is a parody of Japanese idol group [[AKB48]].<ref>{{Cite web | script-title=ko:[\uc778\ud130\ubdf0] \ubcc0\uc694\ud55c \"\uc5f0\uc560\ub294 \uc194\uc9c1\ud558\uac8c\u2026\ub534 \uc9d3 \uc808\ub300 \uc548 \ud574\uc694\"| trans-title = [Interview] Sir John \"Love is honest ... I will not do anything else. \" | author = Dea Won| work = [[Kyunghyang Shinmun|Sports Kyunghang]] | date =1 June 2017| accessdate =2017-07-19 | url =http://sports.khan.co.kr/entertainment/sk_index.html?art_id=201706251639003&sec_id=540101&pt=nv| language = ko }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | title = The hottest stars all belong in \"byh48\"| author = Kim Ji-young| work = [[Korea Herald|K-pop Herald]] | date =1 January 2016| accessdate =1 October 2017 | url =http://kpopherald.com/view.php?ud=201601071729452790214_2| language = en }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:450px\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Note\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2013 || ''Run to the South'' || Cafe member 1 ||\n|-\n| ''[[Cold Eyes]]'' || Parrot ||\n|-\n| ''[[Queen of the Night (2013 film)|Queen of the Night]]'' || Male employee 1 ||\n|-\n| ''[[Way Back Home (2013 film)|Way Back Home]]'' || Gwang-sik ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2014 || ''Animal'' || Soo-yong ||\n|-\n| ''[[No Tears for the Dead]]'' || Electric vehicle engineer ||\n|-\n| ''[[Tazza: The Hidden Card]]'' || Worth ||\n|-\n| ''[[Fashion King (film)|Fashion King]]'' || Duo man 2 ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2015 || ''[[The Beauty Inside (2015 film)|The Beauty Inside]]'' || Sang-baek ||\n|-\n| ''[[Veteran (2015 film)|Veteran]]'' || Yoon Hong-ryeol ||\n|-\n| ''[[The Sound of a Flower]]'' || Chil-sung ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2016 || ''[[The Handmaiden]]'' ||Goo-gai\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Luck Key]]'' || Min-suk ||cameo\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2017 || ''[[Confidential Assignment]]'' || Park Myung-ho ||\n|-\n| ''[[One Line (film)|One Line]]'' || Senior Manager Song ||\n|-\n| ''[[New Trial (film)|New Trial]]'' || Chang-hwan ||\n|-\n| ''[[The Bros]]'' || Lee Joo-bong  ||\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2019 || ''[[Extreme Job]]'' || Detective Young-Ho ||\n|-\n|''[[Call (film)|Call]]''|| Baek Min-hyun||\n|}\n\n===Television series===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Network\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Gunman in Joseon]]''\n| Han Jung-hoon\n| [[KBS2]]\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Divorce Lawyer in Love]]''\n| Lee Kyung\n| [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]\n|-\n| 2015-2016\n| ''[[Reply 1988]]''\n| Ryu Dong-ryong\n| [[TVN (South Korea)|tvN]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2016\n| ''Red Teacher'' ([[Drama City|Drama Special]])\n| Kim Tae-nam\n| KBS2\n|-\n| ''[[Entourage (South Korean TV series)|Entourage]]'' \n| Geo-book (Turtle)\n| tvN\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Radiant Office]]'' \n| Do Ki-taek \n| [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]\n|-\n\n| 2019\n| ''[[Pegasus Market]]'' \n| Moon Seok-goo\n| tvN\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[SF8]]'' \n| TBA\n| MBC\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=wikitable sortable; style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n! Ref.\n|- \n| rowspan=\"9\"|2016\n| <center>InStyle Star Icon</center>\n| New Generation Actor Award\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|''[[Reply 1988]]'', ''[[The Sound of a Flower]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| <center>8th [[Style Icon Asia]]</center>\n| Awesome Swagger\n| {{NA}}\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| <center>11th Max Movie Awards</center>\n| Best Supporting Actor\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[The Beauty Inside (2015 film)|''The Beauty Inside'']]\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| <center>[[52nd Baeksang Arts Awards|52nd]] [[Baeksang Arts Awards]]</center>\n| Best New Actor (TV)\n| rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|''[[Reply 1